04547nam a22006615i 9780691187532DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20182002nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806911875327 a10.1515/97806911875322doi  a(DE-B1597)501674  a(OCoLC)1076395133  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aJL966b.C65 2002eb 7aPOL0110002bisacsh04a306/.0982231 aColburn, Forrest D., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLatin America at the End of Politics /cForrest D. Colburn. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2002  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tChapter 1. Introduction -- tChapter 2. Latin America as a Place -- tChapter 3. Urban Bias -- tChapter 4. An Ideological Vacuum -- tChapter 5. Fragile Democracies -- tChapter 6. The Business of Being in Business -- tChapter 7. Environmental Degradation -- tChapter 8. Malls -- tChapter 9. Crime -- tChapter 10. The Poor -- tChapter 11. Struggling for Gender Equality -- tChapter 12. El Gringo -- tChapter 13. What to Paint? -- tChapter 14. Migration -- tChapter 15. Conclusion -- tIllustrations -- tA Note about Sources -- tBibliography0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAfter decades of ideological struggle, much of it in the service of an elusive socialist ideal, Latin America has embraced liberalism--democracy and unfettered markets. But liberalism has triumphed more by default than through exuberance. The region's democracies are fragile and lethargic. Despite pronounced social inequality, widespread poverty, and other difficulties, the populace is not engaged in deep discussions about state and society. The end of ideological contests has dampened political conflict, but likewise lessened the sense of urgency for solving trenchant problems. Political fatigue and devotion to acquisition have smothered egalitarianism as even an ideal. There is an uneasy social indifference. Latin America at the End of Politics explores this period of circumscribed political passions through deft portrayals of crucial political, economic, social, and cultural issues: governance, entrepreneurs and markets, urban bias, poverty, the struggle for women's equality, consumerism, crime, environmental degradation, art, and migration of the poor. Discussions of these issues are enriched by the poignant narratives of emblematic individuals, many of whom are disoriented by the ideological void of the era. Forrest Colburn's highly original analysis draws on his deep scholarly and personal familiarity with Latin America. The collage of issues discussed, set in a provocative framework, offers a compelling interpretation of Latin America in the aftermath of the last century's ideological battles--and a way to begin to talk about the region's future.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044250240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691187532zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691187532423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691187532.jpg  a978-3-11-044250-2  Princeton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK